                <head>148. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>The United States Government supported the creation of a Volunteer Freedom Corps,
                    to comprise nationals of Eastern European countries (other than East Germany).
                    Major U.S. allies opposed the proposal, and consequently, it died a slow death.
                    Consideration of the Volunteer Freedom Corps is covered extensively in <ref
                        target="frus1952-54v08">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1952–1954, volume VIII</ref>. The
                    Department of State had major reservations about the proposals, some of which
                    were raised by Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_SGWB1">Smith</persName> in
                    the 145th meeting of the National Security Council, May 20, 1953. (<ref
                        target="frus1952-54v08#pg_213">Ibid., pages 213</ref>–<ref
                        target="frus1952-54v08#pg_218">218</ref>)</p>
            </div>
